[{"content":"To see what a **translation** is, please grab the point and move it around.\n\n[[☃ interaction 1]]\n\nNice! You *translated* the point. In geometry, a translation moves a thing up and down or left and right.\n\nHere, try translating this line:\n\n[[☃ interaction 2]]\n\nNotice how the line's disposition remained the same as you moved it. Translations only move things from one place to another; they don't change their arrangement or direction.\n\nNow that we've got a basic understanding of what translations are, let's learn how to use them on the coordinate plane.","images":{},"widgets":{"interaction 1":{"alignment":"default","graded":true,"options":{"elements":[{"key":"movable-point-96a605","options":{"constraint":"none","constraintFn":"0","constraintXMax":"5","constraintXMin":"-5","constraintYMax":"5","constraintYMin":"-5","snap":0.5,"startX":"0","startY":"0","varSubscript":0},"type":"movable-point"}],"graph":{"backgroundImage":{"height":0,"url":null,"width":0},"box":[260,120],"editableSettings":["canvas","graph"],"gridStep":[0.5,2],"labels":["x","y"],"markings":"none","range":[[-5,5],[-5,5]],"rulerLabel":"","rulerTicks":10,"showProtractor":false,"showRuler":false,"snapStep":[1,1],"tickStep":[1,2],"valid":true},"static":false},"static":false,"type":"interaction","version":{"major":0,"minor":0}},"interaction 2":{"alignment":"default","graded":true,"options":{"elements":[{"key":"movable-line-16b1da","options":{"constraint":"none","constraintFn":"0","constraintXMax":"0","constraintXMin":"-10","constraintYMax":"2","constraintYMin":"-10","endSubscript":1,"endX":"5","endY":"5","snap":0.5,"startSubscript":0,"startX":"-5","startY":"-3"},"type":"movable-line"}],"graph":{"backgroundImage":{"height":0,"url":null,"width":0},"box":[260,120],"editableSettings":["canvas","graph"],"gridStep":[1,1],"labels":["x","y"],"markings":"none","range":[[-10,10],[-10,10]],"rulerLabel":"","rulerTicks":10,"showProtractor":false,"showRuler":false,"snapStep":[1,1],"tickStep":[1,1],"valid":true},"static":false},"static":false,"type":"interaction","version":{"major":0,"minor":0}}}},{"content":"# Translations on the coordinate plane\n\nCoordinates allow us to be very precise about the translations we perform.\n\nWithout coordinates, we could say something like, \"We get $\\maroonD{B'}$ by translating $\\blueD{B}$ down and to the right.\"\n\n![](web+graphie://ka-perseus-graphie.s3.amazonaws.com/4cefbcb284fe4e9faa7bb67dc1c55f22534097f9)\n\nBut that's not very precise. If we use a coordinate grid, we can say something more exact: \"We get $\\maroonD{B'}$ by translating $\\blueD{B}$ by 5 units to the right and 4 units down.\"\n\n![](web+graphie://ka-perseus-graphie.s3.amazonaws.com/78f0c6ffa4f435bb27d80c75adbee450ed6d7a71)\n\nMore compactly, we can describe this as **a translation by $\\langle 5,-4 \\rangle$.**\n\nThe negative sign in front of the 4 tells us the vertical shift is downwards instead of upwards. Similarly, a translation to the left is indicated by the first value being negative.\n\n###Sources and images\n\nFor any transformation, we have the **source** figure, which is the figure we are performing the transformation upon, and the **image** figure, which is the result of the transformation. For example, in our translation, the source point was $\\blueD{B}$ and the image point was $\\maroonD{B'}$.\n\nNote that we indicated the image by $\\maroonD{B'}$, pronounced B prime. It is common, when working with transformations, to use the same letter for the image and the source, simply adding the \"prime\" suffix to the image.","images":{"web+graphie://ka-perseus-graphie.s3.amazonaws.com/4cefbcb284fe4e9faa7bb67dc1c55f22534097f9":{"height":255,"width":255},"web+graphie://ka-perseus-graphie.s3.amazonaws.com/78f0c6ffa4f435bb27d80c75adbee450ed6d7a71":{"height":281,"width":281}},"widgets":{}},{"content":"# Let's try some practice problems\n\n[[☃ explanation 1]]\n\n### प्रश्न 1\n\n[[☃ graded-group 1]]\n\n[[☃ explanation 2]]","images":{},"widgets":{"exp